# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-cloud-sql
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] A **cloud database** is a database that typically runs on a cloud computing platform, with access provided as a service.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] There are two common deployment models: users can run databases on the cloud independently, using a virtual machine image, or they can purchase access to a database service maintained by a cloud database provider.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] Cloud databases may use either a relational SQL or a NoSQL data model.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] Database services handle scalability and high availability, while making the underlying software stack transparent to users.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] Cloud platforms allow users to purchase virtual machine instances for a limited time, on which a database can be run.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] Users can upload their own machine image with a database installed or use ready-made machine images that include an optimized installation of a database.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] With a database as a service (DBaaS) model, users pay a cloud provider for database services and computing resources, which may reduce the operational overhead needed to develop and manage databases.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] Users are provided with tools to create and manage database instances, as well as to manage database users.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] Some cloud providers also offer tools for managing database structures and data.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] The design and development of typical systems often use data management and relational databases as key building blocks.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] Advanced queries expressed in SQL work well with the strict relationships imposed by relational databases.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] However, relational database technology was not originally designed for use over distributed systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] This limitation has been addressed through clustering enhancements, although some fundamental operations—such as data synchronization—still require complex and expensive protocols.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] Modern relational databases can exhibit poor performance on data-intensive systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] As a result, the NoSQL paradigm has been adopted within database management systems for cloud-based systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] NoSQL storage does not require fixed table schemas, and join operations are typically avoided.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] NoSQL databases have been shown to provide efficient horizontal scalability, high performance, and ease of integration into cloud applications.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] Additionally, data models that rely on simplified relay algorithms have been employed in data-intensive cloud mapping applications specific to virtual frameworks.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] It is also important to differentiate between cloud databases which are relational (SQL) and those that are non-relational (NoSQL).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] SQL databases can run in the cloud either on virtual machines or as a managed service, depending on the vendor.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] While SQL databases are generally easy to scale vertically, horizontal scalability presents a greater challenge.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] making them well suited to cloud environments.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] However, many contemporary applications are built around a relational (SQL) data model, so adopting NoSQL databases often requires significant changes to application code.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] or similar variants), and key-value store data types.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] Multi-model databases combine relational and non-relational capabilities, providing a standard SQL interface to users and applications.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] Native multi-model databases support multiple data models with a single core, facilitating their use in applications built around SQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/database-as-a-service] The following table lists notable database vendors that offer cloud database services, classified by deployment model—machine image or database as a service—and by data model (SQL or NoSQL).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] There is now more dependence on these systems as a result of modernization.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] For example, to carry out their regular daily tasks, hospitals and data centers need their systems to be highly available.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Availability refers to the ability of the user to access a service or system, whether to submit new work, update or modify existing work, or retrieve the results of previous work.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] If a user cannot access the system, it is considered *unavailable from the user's perspective*.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] The term *downtime* is generally used to refer to describe periods when a system is unavailable.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] As such, network resilience touches a very wide range of topics.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] In order to increase the resilience of a given communication network, the probable challenges and risks have to be identified and appropriate resilience metrics have to be defined for the service to be protected.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] The importance of network resilience is continuously increasing, as communication networks are becoming a fundamental component in the operation of critical infrastructures.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Consequently, recent efforts focus on interpreting and improving network and computing resilience with applications to critical infrastructures.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] As an example, one can consider as a resilience objective the provisioning of services over the network, instead of the services of the network itself.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] This may require coordinated response from both the network and from the services running on top of the network.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Resilience and survivability are interchangeably used according to the specific context of a given study.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] There are three principles of systems design in reliability engineering that can help achieve high availability.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] In redundant systems, the crossover point itself tends to become a single point of failure.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Reliable systems must provide for reliable crossover.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] If the two principles above are observed, then a user may never see a failure – but the maintenance activity must.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] A distinction can be made between scheduled and unscheduled downtime.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Typically, scheduled downtime is a result of maintenance that is disruptive to system operation and usually cannot be avoided with a currently installed system design.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Scheduled downtime events might include patches to system software that require a reboot or system configuration changes that only take effect upon a reboot.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] In general, scheduled downtime is usually the result of some logical, management-initiated event.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Unscheduled downtime events typically arise from some physical event, such as a hardware or software failure or environmental anomaly.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] If users can be warned away from scheduled downtimes, then the distinction is useful.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] But if the requirement is for true high availability, then downtime is downtime whether or not it is scheduled.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Many computing sites exclude scheduled downtime from availability calculations, assuming that it has little or no impact upon the computing user community.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] By doing this, they can claim to have phenomenally high availability, which might give the illusion of continuous availability.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] For certain systems, scheduled downtime does not matter, for example, system downtime at an office building after everybody has gone home for the night.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Availability is usually expressed as a percentage of uptime in a given year.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] The following table shows the downtime that will be allowed for a particular percentage of availability, presuming that the system is required to operate continuously.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Service level agreements often refer to monthly downtime or availability in order to calculate service credits to match monthly billing cycles.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] The following table shows the translation from a given availability percentage to the corresponding amount of time a system would be unavailable.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Availability is often quoted in terms of "nines", with 90% availability being called "one nine", 99% "two nines", 99.9% "three nines" and so on.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] As the number of nines gets larger, the availability targets get exponentially more stringent.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] The terms uptime and availability are often used interchangeably but do not always refer to the same thing.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] For example, a system can be "up" with its services not "available" in the case of a network outage.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Or a system undergoing software maintenance can be "available" to be worked on by a system administrator, but its services do not appear "up" to the end user or customer.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] A simple mnemonic rule states that *5 nines* allows approximately 5 minutes of downtime per year.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Variants can be derived by multiplying or dividing by 10: 4 nines is 50 minutes and 3 nines is 500 minutes.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] In the opposite direction, 6 nines is 0.5 minutes (30 sec) and 7 nines is 3 seconds.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Another memory trick to calculate the allowed downtime duration for an " n -nines" availability percentage is to use the formula $8.64\times 10^{4-n}$ seconds per day.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] For example, 90% ("one nine") yields the exponent $4-1=3$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{3}$ seconds per day.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Also, 99.999% ("five nines") gives the exponent $4-5=-1$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{-1}$ seconds per day.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Percentages of a particular order of magnitude are sometimes referred to by the number of nines or "class of nines" in the digits.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] For example, electricity that is delivered without interruptions (blackouts, brownouts or surges) 99.999% of the time would have 5 nines reliability, or class five.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] In particular, the term is used in connection with mainframes or enterprise computing, often as part of a service-level agreement.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Similarly, percentages ending in a 5 have conventional names, traditionally the number of nines, then "five", so 99.95% is "three nines five", abbreviated 3N5.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] This is casually referred to as "three and a half nines", but this is incorrect: a 5 is only a factor of 2, while a 9 is a factor of 10, so a 5 is 0.3 nines (per below formula: $\log _{10}2\approx 0.3$ ): 99.95% availability is 3.3 nines, not 3.5 nines.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] More simply, going from 99.9% availability to 99.95% availability is a factor of 2 (0.1% to 0.05% unavailability), but going from 99.95% to 99.99% availability is a factor of 5 (0.05% to 0.01% unavailability), over twice as much.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] A similar measurement is sometimes used to describe the purity of substances.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] In general, the number of nines is not often used by a network engineer when modeling and measuring availability because it is hard to apply in formula.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] More often, the unavailability expressed as a probability (like 0.00001), or a downtime per year is quoted.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Availability specified as a number of nines is often seen in marketing documents.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] The use of the "nines" has been called into question, since it does not appropriately reflect that the impact of unavailability varies with its time of occurrence.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] For large amounts of 9s, the "unavailability" index (measure of downtime rather than uptime) is easier to handle.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] For example, this is why an "unavailability" rather than availability metric is used in hard disk or data link bit error rates.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Sometimes the humorous term "nine fives" (55.5555555%) is used to contrast with "five nines" (99.999%), though this is not an actual goal, but rather a sarcastic reference to something totally failing to meet any reasonable target.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Availability measurement is subject to some degree of interpretation.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] A system that has been up for 365 days in a non-leap year might have been eclipsed by a network failure that lasted for 9 hours during a peak usage period; the user community will see the system as unavailable, whereas the system administrator will claim 100% uptime.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] However, given the true definition of availability, the system will be approximately 99.9% available, or three nines (8751 hours of available time out of 8760 hours per non-leap year).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Also, systems experiencing performance problems are often deemed partially or entirely unavailable by users, even when the systems are continuing to function.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Similarly, unavailability of select application functions might go unnoticed by administrators yet be devastating to users – a true availability measure is holistic.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Availability must be measured to be determined, ideally with comprehensive monitoring tools ("instrumentation") that are themselves highly available.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] An alternative metric is mean time between failures (MTBF).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Recovery time (or estimated time of repair (ETR), also known as recovery time objective (RTO) is closely related to availability, that is the total time required for a planned outage or the time required to fully recover from an unplanned outage.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Another metric is mean time to recovery (MTTR).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Recovery time could be infinite with certain system designs and failures, i.e. full recovery is impossible.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] One such example is a fire or flood that destroys a data center and its systems when there is no secondary disaster recovery data center.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Another related concept is data availability, that is the degree to which databases and other information storage systems faithfully record and report system transactions.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Information management often focuses separately on data availability, or Recovery Point Objective, in order to determine acceptable (or actual) data loss with various failure events.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Some users can tolerate application service interruptions but cannot tolerate data loss.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] A service level agreement ("SLA") formalizes an organization's availability objectives and requirements.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] High availability is one of the primary requirements of the control systems in unmanned vehicles and autonomous maritime vessels.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] If the controlling system becomes unavailable, the Ground Combat Vehicle (GCV) or ASW Continuous Trail Unmanned Vessel (ACTUV) would be lost.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] On one hand, adding more components to an overall system design can undermine efforts to achieve high availability because complex systems inherently have more potential failure points and are more difficult to implement correctly.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] More advanced system designs allow for systems to be patched and upgraded without compromising service availability (see load balancing and failover).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] High availability requires less human intervention to restore operation in complex systems; the reason for this being that the most common cause for outages is human error.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] On the other hand, redundancy is used to create systems with high levels of availability (e.g. popular ecommerce websites).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] In this case it is required to have high levels of failure detectability and avoidance of common cause failures.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] If redundant parts are used in parallel and have independent failure (e.g. by not being within the same data center), they can exponentially increase the availability and make the overall system highly available.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] So for example if each of your components has only 50% availability, by using 10 of components in parallel, you can achieve 99.9023% availability.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Two kinds of redundancy are passive redundancy and active redundancy.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Passive redundancy is used to achieve high availability by including enough excess capacity in the design to accommodate a performance decline.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] The simplest example is a boat with two separate engines driving two separate propellers.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] The boat continues toward its destination despite failure of a single engine or propeller.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] A more complex example is multiple redundant power generation facilities within a large system involving electric power transmission.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Malfunction of single components is not considered to be a failure unless the resulting performance decline exceeds the specification limits for the entire system.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Active redundancy is used in complex systems to achieve high availability with no performance decline.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Multiple items of the same kind are incorporated into a design that includes a method to detect failure and automatically reconfigure the system to bypass failed items using a voting scheme.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] This is used with complex computing systems that are linked.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Internet routing is derived from early work by Birman and Joseph in this area.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Active redundancy may introduce more complex failure modes into a system, such as continuous system reconfiguration due to faulty voting logic.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Fault instrumentation can be used in systems with limited redundancy to achieve high availability.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Maintenance actions occur during brief periods of downtime only after a fault indicator activates.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Failure is only significant if this occurs during a mission critical period.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Modeling and simulation is used to evaluate the theoretical reliability for large systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] The outcome of this kind of model is used to evaluate different design options.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] A model of the entire system is created, and the model is stressed by removing components.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] Redundancy simulation involves the N-x criteria.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] N represents the total number of components in the system. x is the number of components used to stress the system.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] N-1 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where one component is faulted.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] N-2 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where two component are faulted simultaneously.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] A survey among academic availability experts in 2010 ranked reasons for unavailability of enterprise IT systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] A book on the factors themselves was published in 2003.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/high-availability] In a 1998 report from IBM Global Services, unavailable systems were estimated to have cost American businesses $4.54 billion in 1996, due to lost productivity and revenues.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL is free and open-source software under the terms of the GNU General Public License, and is also available under a variety of proprietary licenses.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL was owned and sponsored by the Swedish company MySQL AB, which was bought by Sun Microsystems (now Oracle Corporation).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] In 2010, when Oracle acquired Sun, Widenius forked the open-source MySQL project to create MariaDB.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL has stand-alone clients that allow users to interact directly with a MySQL database using SQL, but more often, MySQL is used with other programs to implement applications that need relational database capability.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL is a component of the LAMP web application software stack (and others), which is an acronym for *Linux, Apache, MySQL, Perl/PHP/Python*.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL is used by many database-driven web applications, including Drupal, Joomla, phpBB, and WordPress.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL is also used by many popular websites, including Facebook, Flickr, MediaWiki, Twitter, and YouTube.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Its SQL parser is written in yacc, but it uses a home-brewed lexical analyzer.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL works on many system platforms, including AIX, BSDi, FreeBSD, HP-UX, ArcaOS, eComStation, IBM i, IRIX, Linux, macOS, Microsoft Windows, NetBSD, Novell NetWare, OpenBSD, OpenSolaris, OS/2 Warp, QNX, Oracle Solaris, Symbian, SunOS, SCO OpenServer, SCO UnixWare, Sanos and Tru64.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The MySQL server software itself and the client libraries use dual-licensing distribution.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] They are offered under GPL version 2, or a proprietary license.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Support can be obtained from the official manual.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Free support additionally is available in different IRC channels and forums.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Oracle offers paid support via its MySQL Enterprise products.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] They differ in the scope of services and in price.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Additionally, a number of third party organisations exist to provide support and services.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL has received positive reviews, and reviewers noticed it "performs extremely well in the average case" and that the "developer interfaces are there, and the documentation (not to mention feedback in the real world via Web sites and the like) is very, very good".
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] It has also been tested to be a "fast, stable and true multi-user, multi-threaded SQL database server".
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL was created by a Swedish company, MySQL AB, founded by Swedes David Axmark and Allan Larsson, along with Finn Michael "Monty" Widenius.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Original development of MySQL by Widenius and Axmark began in 1994.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The first version of MySQL appeared on 23 May 1995.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] It was initially created for personal usage from mSQL based on the low-level language ISAM, which the creators considered too slow and inflexible.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] They created a new SQL interface, while keeping the same API as mSQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] By keeping the API consistent with the mSQL system, many developers were able to use MySQL instead of the (proprietarily licensed) mSQL antecedent.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Work on version 6 stopped after the Sun Microsystems acquisition.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The MySQL Cluster product uses version 7.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The decision was made to jump to version 8 as the next major version number.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] On 15 June 2001, NuSphere sued MySQL AB, TcX DataKonsult AB and its original authors Michael ("Monty") Widenius and David Axmark in U.S.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] District Court in Boston for "breach of contract, tortious interference with third party contracts and relationships and unfair competition".
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] In 2002, MySQL AB sued Progress NuSphere for copyright and trademark infringement in United States district court.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] NuSphere had allegedly violated MySQL AB's copyright by linking MySQL's GPL'ed code with NuSphere Gemini table without being in compliance with the license.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] After a preliminary hearing before Judge Patti Saris on 27 February 2002, the parties entered settlement talks and eventually settled.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] In October 2005, Oracle Corporation acquired Innobase OY, the Finnish company that developed the third-party InnoDB storage engine that allows MySQL to provide such functionality as transactions and foreign keys.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] After the acquisition, an Oracle press release mentioned that the contracts that make the company's software available to MySQL AB would be due for renewal (and presumably renegotiation) some time in 2006.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] During the MySQL Users Conference in April 2006, MySQL AB issued a press release that confirmed that MySQL AB and Innobase OY agreed to a "multi-year" extension of their licensing agreement.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] In February 2006, Oracle Corporation acquired Sleepycat Software, makers of the Berkeley DB, a database engine providing the basis for another MySQL storage engine.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] This had little effect, as Berkeley DB was not widely used, and was dropped (due to lack of use) in MySQL 5.1.12, a pre-GA release of MySQL 5.1 released in October 2006.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] In January 2008, Sun Microsystems bought MySQL AB for $1 billion.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] In April 2009, Oracle Corporation entered into an agreement to purchase Sun Microsystems, then owners of MySQL copyright and trademark.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Sun's board of directors unanimously approved the deal.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] It was also approved by Sun's shareholders, and by the U.S. government on 20 August 2009.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] On 14 December 2009, Oracle pledged to continue to enhance MySQL as it had done for the previous four years.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] A movement against Oracle's acquisition of MySQL AB, to "Save MySQL" from Oracle was started by one of the MySQL AB founders, Monty Widenius.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The petition of 50,000+ developers and users called upon the European Commission to block approval of the acquisition.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] At the same time, some Free Software opinion leaders (including Pamela Jones of Groklaw, Jan Wildeboer and Carlo Piana, who also acted as co-counsel in the merger regulation procedure) advocated for the unconditional approval of the merger.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] As part of the negotiations with the European Commission, Oracle committed that MySQL server will continue until at least 2015 to use the dual-licensing strategy long used by MySQL AB, with proprietary and GPL versions available.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The antitrust of the EU had been "pressuring it to divest MySQL as a condition for approval of the merger".
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] But the US Department of Justice, at the request of Oracle, pressured the EU to approve the merger unconditionally.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The European Commission eventually unconditionally approved Oracle's acquisition of MySQL AB on 21 January 2010.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] In January 2010, before Oracle's acquisition of MySQL AB, Monty Widenius started a GPL-only fork, MariaDB.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MariaDB is based on the same code base as MySQL server 5.5 and aims to maintain compatibility with Oracle-provided versions.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL is offered under two different editions: the open source MySQL Community Server and the proprietary Enterprise Server.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL Enterprise Server is differentiated by a series of proprietary extensions which install as server plugins, but otherwise shares the version numbering system and is built from the same code base.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The developers release minor updates of the MySQL Server approximately every two months.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The sources can be obtained from MySQL's website or from MySQL's GitHub repository, both under the GPL license.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] When using some storage engines other than the default of InnoDB, MySQL does not comply with the full SQL standard for some of the implemented functionality, including foreign key references.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Check constraints are parsed but ignored by all storage engines before MySQL version 8.0.15.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Up until MySQL 5.7, triggers are limited to one per action / timing, meaning that at most one trigger can be defined to be executed after an INSERT operation, and one before INSERT on the same table.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Before MySQL 8.0.28, inbuilt functions like UNIX_TIMESTAMP() would return 0 after 03:14:07 UTC on 19 January 2038.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] In 2017, an attempt to solve the problem was submitted, but was not used for the final solution that was shipped in 2022.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL can be built and installed manually from source code, but it is more commonly installed from a binary package unless special customizations are required.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] On most Linux distributions, the package management system can download and install MySQL with minimal effort, though further configuration is often required to adjust security and optimization settings.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Though MySQL began as a low-end alternative to more powerful proprietary databases, it has gradually evolved to support higher-scale needs as well.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] It is still most commonly used in small to medium scale single-server deployments, either as a component in a LAMP-based web application or as a standalone database server.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Much of MySQL's appeal originates in its relative simplicity and ease of use, which is enabled by an ecosystem of open source tools such as phpMyAdmin.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] In the medium range, MySQL can be scaled by deploying it on more powerful hardware, such as a multi-processor server with gigabytes of memory.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] There are, however, limits to how far performance can scale on a single server ('scaling up'), so on larger scales, multi-server MySQL ('scaling out') deployments are required to provide improved performance and reliability.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] A typical high-end configuration can include a powerful source database (formerly known as master database) which handles data write operations and is replicated to multiple replicas (formerly known as slaves) that handle all read operations.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The source server continually pushes binlog events to connected replicas so in the event of failure a replica can be promoted to become the new source, minimizing downtime.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Further improvements in performance can be achieved by caching the results from database queries in memory using memcached, or breaking down a database into smaller chunks called shards which can be spread across a number of distributed server clusters.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Oracle MySQL offers a high availability solution with a mix of tools including the MySQL router and the MySQL shell.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] They are based on Group Replication, open source tools.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MariaDB offers a similar offer in terms of products.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL can also be run on cloud computing platforms such as Microsoft Azure, Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud, and Oracle Cloud Infrastructure.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] In this implementation, cloud users can upload a machine image of their own with MySQL installed, or use a ready-made machine image with an optimized installation of MySQL on it, such as the one provided by Amazon EC2.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Some cloud platforms offer MySQL "as a service".
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] In this configuration, application owners do not have to install and maintain the MySQL database on their own.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Instead, the database service provider takes responsibility for installing and maintaining the database, and application owners pay according to their usage.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Notable cloud-based MySQL services are the Amazon Relational Database Service; Oracle MySQL HeatWave Database Service, Azure Database for MySQL, Rackspace; HP Converged Cloud; Heroku and Jelastic.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] In this model the database service provider takes responsibility for maintaining the host and database.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] A graphical user interface (GUI) is a type of interface that allows users to interact with electronic devices or programs through graphical icons and visual indicators such as secondary notation, as opposed to text-based interfaces, typed command labels or text navigation.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Third-party proprietary and free graphical administration applications (or "front ends") are available that integrate with MySQL and enable users to work with database structure and data visually.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL Workbench is the integrated environment for MySQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] It was developed by MySQL AB, and enables users to graphically administer MySQL databases and visually design database structures.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL Workbench is available in three editions, the regular free and open source *Community Edition* which may be downloaded from the MySQL website, and the proprietary *Standard Edition* which extends and improves the feature set of the Community Edition, and the MySQL Cluster CGE.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] A command-line interface is a means of interacting with a computer program where the user issues commands to the program by typing in successive lines of text (command lines).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL ships with many command line tools, from which the main interface is the mysql client.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL Utilities is a set of utilities designed to perform common maintenance and administrative tasks.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Originally included as part of the MySQL Workbench, the utilities are a stand-alone download available from Oracle.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Percona Toolkit is a cross-platform toolkit for MySQL, developed in Perl.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Percona Toolkit can be used to prove replication is working correctly, fix corrupted data, automate repetitive tasks, and speed up servers.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Percona Toolkit is included with several Linux distributions such as CentOS and Debian, and packages are available for Fedora and Ubuntu as well.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Percona Toolkit was originally developed as Maatkit, but as of late 2011, Maatkit is no longer developed.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL shell is a tool for interactive use and administration of the MySQL database.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] It supports JavaScript, Python or SQL modes and it can be used for administration and access purposes.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Many programming languages with language-specific APIs include libraries for accessing MySQL databases.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] These include MySQL Connector/Net for .NET/CLI Languages, and the JDBC driver for Java.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MySQL offers Connector/C++ for interfacing with C++ in namespace `mysqlx`.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] In addition, an ODBC interface called MySQL Connector/ODBC allows additional programming languages that support the ODBC interface to communicate with a MySQL database, such as ASP or ColdFusion.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The HTSQL – URL-based query method also ships with a MySQL adapter, allowing direct interaction between a MySQL database and any web client via structured URLs.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Other drivers exists for languages like Python or Node.js.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] MariaDB is a community-developed fork of the MySQL relational database management system intended to remain free under the GNU GPL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The fork has been led by the original developers of MySQL, who forked it due to concerns over its acquisition by Oracle.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Percona Server for MySQL, forked by Percona, aims to retain close compatibility to the official MySQL releases.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Also included in Percona Server for MySQL is XtraDB, Percona's fork of the InnoDB Storage Engine.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Drizzle was a free software/open source relational database management system (DBMS) that was forked from the now-defunct 6.0 development branch of the MySQL DBMS.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Like MySQL, Drizzle had a client/server architecture and uses SQL as its primary command language.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Drizzle was distributed under version 2 and 3 of the GNU General Public License (GPL) with portions, including the protocol drivers and replication messaging under the BSD license.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Thus, WebScaleSQL opened a path toward deduplicating the efforts each company had been putting into maintaining its own branch of MySQL, and toward bringing together more developers.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] By combining the efforts of these companies and incorporating various changes and new features into MySQL, WebScaleSQL aimed at supporting the deployment of MySQL in large-scale environments.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The project's source code is licensed under version 2 of the GNU General Public License, and is hosted on GitHub.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] The OurDelta distribution, created by the Australian company Open Query (later acquired by Catalyst IT Australia), had two versions: 5.0, which was based on MySQL, and 5.1, which was based on MariaDB.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] It included patches developed by Open Query and by other notable members of the MySQL community including Jeremy Cole and Google.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/mysql] Once the patches were incorporated into the MariaDB mainline, OurDelta's objectives were achieved and OurDelta passed on its build and packaging toolchain to Monty Program (now MariaDB Plc).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The PostgreSQL Global Development Group focuses only on developing a database engine and closely related components.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] This core is, technically, what comprises PostgreSQL itself, but there is an extensive developer community and ecosystem that provides other important feature sets that might, traditionally, be provided by a proprietary software vendor.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] These include special-purpose database engine features, like those needed to support a geospatial or temporal database or features which emulate other database products.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Also available from third parties are a wide variety of user and machine interface features, such as graphical user interfaces or load balancing and high availability toolsets.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The large third-party PostgreSQL support network of people, companies, products, and projects, even though not part of The PostgreSQL Development Group, are essential to the PostgreSQL database engine's adoption and use and make up the PostgreSQL ecosystem writ large.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL was originally named POSTGRES, referring to its origins as a successor to the Ingres database developed at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] After a review in 2007, the development team decided to keep the name PostgreSQL and the alias Postgres.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL evolved from the Ingres project at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In 1982, the leader of the Ingres team, Michael Stonebraker, left Berkeley to make a proprietary version of Ingres.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] He returned to Berkeley in 1985, and began a post-Ingres project to address the problems with contemporary database systems that had become increasingly clear during the early 1980s.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] He won the Turing Award in 2014 for these and other projects, and techniques pioneered in them.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The new project, POSTGRES, aimed to add the fewest features needed to completely support data types.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] These features included the ability to define types and to fully describe relationships – something used widely, but maintained entirely by the user.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In POSTGRES, the database understood relationships, and could retrieve information in related tables in a natural way using *rules*.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] POSTGRES used many of the ideas of Ingres, but not its code.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Starting in 1986, published papers described the basis of the system, and a prototype version was shown at the 1988 ACM SIGMOD Conference.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The team released version 1 to a small number of users in June 1989, followed by version 2 with a re-written rules system in June 1990.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Version 3, released in 1991, again re-wrote the rules system, and added support for multiple storage managers and an improved query engine.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] By 1993, the number of users began to overwhelm the project with requests for support and features.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] After releasing version 4.2 on June 30, 1994 – primarily a cleanup – the project ended.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Berkeley released POSTGRES under an MIT License variant, which enabled other developers to use the code for any use.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] At the time, POSTGRES used an Ingres-influenced POSTQUEL query language interpreter, which could be interactively used with a console application named monitor.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In 1994, Berkeley graduate students Andrew Yu and Jolly Chen replaced the POSTQUEL query language interpreter with one for the SQL query language, creating Postgres95.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The monitor console was also replaced by psql.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Yu and Chen announced the first version (0.01) to beta testers on May 5, 1995.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Version 1.0 of Postgres95 was announced on September 5, 1995, with a more liberal license that enabled the software to be freely modifiable.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] On July 8, 1996, Marc Fournier at Hub.org Networking Services provided the first non-university development server for the open-source development effort.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] With the participation of Bruce Momjian and Vadim B.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Mikheev, work began to stabilize the code inherited from Berkeley.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed to PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The online presence at the website PostgreSQL.org began on October 22, 1996.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The first PostgreSQL release formed version 6.0 on January 29, 1997.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Since then developers and volunteers around the world have maintained the software as The PostgreSQL Global Development Group.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The project continues to make releases available under its free and open-source software PostgreSQL License.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Code comes from contributions from proprietary vendors, support companies, and open-source programmers.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] As of 2025, PostgreSQL is on major release version 18 which is notable in implementing asynchronous I/O (AIO), enabling database users to perform concurrent I/O tasks like readahead and sequential scan.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages concurrency through multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), which gives each transaction a "snapshot" of the database, allowing changes to be made without affecting other transactions.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] This largely eliminates the need for read locks, and ensures the database maintains ACID principles.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL offers four levels of transaction isolation: Read Uncommitted, Read Committed, Repeatable Read and Serializable.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Because PostgreSQL is immune to dirty reads, requesting a Read Uncommitted transaction isolation level provides read committed instead.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports full serializability via the serializable snapshot isolation (SSI) method.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The PostgreSQL MVCC implementation is prone to performance issues that require tuning when under a heavy write load which updates existing rows.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in binary replication based on shipping the changes (write-ahead logs (WAL)) to replica nodes asynchronously, with the ability to run read-only queries against these replicated nodes.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] This allows splitting read traffic among multiple nodes efficiently.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Earlier replication software that allowed similar read scaling normally relied on adding replication triggers to the master, increasing load.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in synchronous replication that ensures that, for each write transaction, the master waits until at least one replica node has written the data to its transaction log.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Unlike other database systems, the durability of a transaction (whether it is asynchronous or synchronous) can be specified per-database, per-user, per-session or even per-transaction.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] This can be useful for workloads that do not require such guarantees, and may not be wanted for all data as it slows down performance due to the requirement of the confirmation of the transaction reaching the synchronous standby.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Standby servers can be synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Synchronous standby servers can be specified in the configuration which determines which servers are candidates for synchronous replication.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The first in the list that is actively streaming will be used as the current synchronous server.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] When this fails, the system fails over to the next in line.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL's replication can trigger conflicts between the primary and standby servers, particularly whenever tuples are prematurely deleted from the standby server despite ongoing queries accessing them.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] To address this, PostgreSQL includes a feedback flag where the standby server proactively informs the primary server of any ongoing queries to mitigate this type of conflict.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Synchronous multi-master replication is not included in the PostgreSQL core.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Postgres-XC which is based on PostgreSQL provides scalable synchronous multi-master replication.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] It is licensed under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] A related project is called Postgres-XL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Bidirectional replication (BDR) is an asynchronous multi-master replication system for PostgreSQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Tools such as repmgr make managing replication clusters easier.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Several asynchronous trigger-based replication packages are available.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in support for regular B-tree and hash table indexes, and four index access methods: generalized search trees (GiST), generalized inverted indexes (GIN), Space-Partitioned GiST (SP-GiST) and Block Range Indexes (BRIN).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In addition, user-defined index methods can be created, although this is quite an involved process.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL schemas are namespaces, allowing objects of the same kind and name to co-exist in a single database.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] They are not to be confused with a database schema—the abstract, structural, organizational specification which defines how every table's data relates to data within other tables.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] All PostgreSQL database objects, except for a few global objects such as roles and tablespaces, exist within a schema.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] They cannot be nested, schemas cannot contain schemas.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The permission system controls access to schemas and their content.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] By default, newly created databases have only a single schema called *public* but other schemas can be added and the public schema isn't mandatory.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] A `search_path` setting determines the order in which PostgreSQL checks schemas for unqualified objects (those without a prefixed schema).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] By default, it is set to `$user, public` (`$user` refers to the currently connected database user).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] This default can be set on a database or role level, but as it is a session parameter, it can be freely changed (even multiple times) during a client session, affecting that session only.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Non-existent schemas, or other schemas not accessible to the logged-in user, that are listed in search_path are silently skipped during object lookup.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] New objects are created in whichever valid schema (one that can be accessed) appears first in the search_path.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In addition, users can create their own data types which can usually be made fully indexable via PostgreSQL's indexing infrastructures – GiST, GIN, SP-GiST.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Examples of these include the geographic information system (GIS) data types from the PostGIS project for PostgreSQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] There is also a data type called a *domain*, which is the same as any other data type but with optional constraints defined by the creator of that domain.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] This means any data entered into a column using the domain will have to conform to whichever constraints were defined as part of the domain.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] A data type that represents a range of data can be used which are called range types.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] These can be discrete ranges (e.g. all integer values 1 to 10) or continuous ranges (e.g., any time between 10:00 am and 11:00 am).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The built-in range types available include ranges of integers, big integers, decimal numbers, time stamps (with and without time zone) and dates.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Custom range types can be created to make new types of ranges available, such as IP address ranges using the inet type as a base, or float ranges using the float data type as a base.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Range types support inclusive and exclusive range boundaries using the [] and () characters respectively.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] (e.g., `[4,9)` represents all integers starting from and including 4 up to but not including 9.) Range types are also compatible with existing operators used to check for overlap, containment, right of etc.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Tables can be set to inherit their characteristics from a *parent* table.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Data in child tables will appear to exist in the parent tables, unless data is selected from the parent table using the ONLY keyword, i.e.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Adding a column in the parent table will cause that column to appear in the child table.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Inheritance can be used to implement table partitioning, using either triggers or rules to direct inserts to the parent table into the proper child tables.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In particular, table constraints are not currently inheritable.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] All check constraints and not-null constraints on a parent table are automatically inherited by its children.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Other types of constraints (unique, primary key, and foreign key constraints) are not inherited.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Inheritance provides a way to map the features of generalization hierarchies depicted in entity–relationship diagrams (ERDs) directly into the PostgreSQL database.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL can link to other systems to retrieve data via foreign data wrappers (FDWs).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] These can take the form of any data source, such as a file system, another relational database management system (RDBMS), or a web service.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] This means that regular database queries can use these data sources like regular tables, and even join multiple data-sources together.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports a binary communication protocol that allows applications to connect to the database server.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The protocol is versioned (currently 3.0, as of PostgreSQL 7.4) and has a detailed specification.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The official client implementation of this communication protocol is a C API, libpq.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In addition, the officially supported ECPG tool allows SQL commands to be embedded in C code.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Both are part of the standard PostgreSQL distribution.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Third-party libraries for connecting to PostgreSQL are available for many programming languages, including C++, Java, Julia, Python, Node.js, Go, and Rust.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Procedural languages allow developers to extend the database with custom subroutines (functions), often called *stored procedures*.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] These functions can be used to build database triggers (functions invoked on modification of certain data) and custom data types and aggregate functions.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Procedural languages can also be invoked without defining a function, using a DO command at SQL level.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Languages are divided into two groups: Procedures written in *safe* languages are sandboxed and can be safely created and used by any user.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Procedures written in *unsafe* languages can only be created by superusers, because they allow bypassing a database's security restrictions, but can also access sources external to the database.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Some languages like Perl provide both safe and unsafe versions.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In addition, PostgreSQL allows procedural languages to be loaded into the database through extensions.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Three language extensions are included with PostgreSQL to support Perl, Tcl, and Python.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] For Python, the current Python 3 is used, and the discontinued Python 2 is no longer supported as of PostgreSQL 15.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Both were supported previously, defaulting to Python 2, while old and new versions couldn't be used in the same session.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] External projects provide support for many other languages, including PL/Java, JavaScript (PL/V8), PL/Julia, PL/R, PL/Ruby, and others.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Triggers are events triggered by the action of SQL data manipulation language (DML) statements.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] For example, an INSERT statement might activate a trigger that checks if the values of the statement are valid.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Most triggers are only activated by either INSERT or UPDATE statements.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Triggers are fully supported and can be attached to tables.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Triggers can be per-column and conditional, in that UPDATE triggers can target specific columns of a table, and triggers can be told to execute under a set of conditions as specified in the trigger's WHERE clause.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Triggers can be attached to views by using the INSTEAD OF condition.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Multiple triggers are fired in alphabetical order.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In addition to calling functions written in the native PL/pgSQL, triggers can also invoke functions written in other languages like PL/Python or PL/Perl.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL provides an asynchronous messaging system that is accessed through the NOTIFY, LISTEN and UNLISTEN commands.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] A session can issue a NOTIFY command, along with the user-specified channel and an optional payload, to mark a particular event occurring.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Other sessions are able to detect these events by issuing a LISTEN command, which can listen to a particular channel.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] This functionality can be used for a wide variety of purposes, such as letting other sessions know when a table has updated or for separate applications to detect when a particular action has been performed.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Such a system prevents the need for continuous polling by applications to see if anything has yet changed, and reducing unnecessary overhead.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Notifications are fully transactional, in that messages are not sent until the transaction they were sent from is committed.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] This eliminates the problem of messages being sent for an action being performed which is then rolled back.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Many connectors for PostgreSQL provide support for this notification system (including libpq, JDBC, Npgsql, psycopg and node.js) so it can be used by external applications.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL can act as an effective, persistent "pub/sub" server or job server by combining LISTEN with FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Rules allow the "query tree" of an incoming query to be rewritten; they are an, automatically invoked, macro language for SQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] "Query Re-Write Rules" are attached to a table/class and "Re-Write" the incoming DML (select, insert, update, and/or delete) into one or more queries that either replace the original DML statement or execute in addition to it.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Query Re-Write occurs after DML statement parsing and before query planning.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The functionality rules provide was, in almost every way, later duplicated with the introduction of newer types of triggers.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The use of triggers is usually preferred over rules as it is easier to reason about trigger behavior and interactions than when equivalent rules are used.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL server is process-based (not threaded), and uses one operating system process per database session.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Multiple sessions are automatically spread across all available CPUs by the operating system.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Many types of queries can also be parallelized across multiple background worker processes, taking advantage of multiple CPUs or cores.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Client applications can use threads and create multiple database connections from each thread.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages its internal security on a per-role basis.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] A role is generally regarded to be a user (a role that can log in), or a group (a role of which other roles are members).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Permissions can be granted or revoked on any object down to the column level, and can allow or prevent the visibility/creation/alteration/deletion of objects at the database, schema, table, and row levels.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL's SECURITY LABEL feature (extension to SQL standards), allows for additional security; with a bundled loadable module that supports label-based mandatory access control (MAC) based on Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) security policy.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The GSSAPI, SSPI, Kerberos, peer, ident and certificate methods can also use a specified "map" file that lists which users matched by that authentication system are allowed to connect as a specific database user.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] These methods are specified in the cluster's host-based authentication configuration file (pg_hba.conf), which determines what connections are allowed.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] This allows control over which user can connect to which database, where they can connect from (IP address, IP address range, domain socket), which authentication system will be enforced, and whether the connection must use Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL claims high, but not complete, conformance with the latest SQL standard ("as of the version 17 release in September 2024, PostgreSQL conforms to at least 170 of the 177 mandatory features for SQL:2023 Core conformance", and no other databases fully conformed to it).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] One exception is the handling of unquoted identifiers like table or column names.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In PostgreSQL they are folded, internally, to lower case characters whereas the standard says that unquoted identifiers should be folded to upper case.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Thus, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO` not `foo` according to the standard.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Other shortcomings concern the absence of temporal tables allowing automatic logging of row versions during transactions with the possibility of browsing in time (FOR SYSTEM TIME predicate), although relatively SQL compliant third-party extensions are available.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Many informal performance studies of PostgreSQL have been done.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Performance improvements aimed at improving scalability began heavily with version 8.1.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Simple benchmarks between version 8.0 and version 8.4 showed that the latter was more than ten times faster on read-only workloads and at least 7.5 times faster on both read and write workloads.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The first industry-standard and peer-validated benchmark was completed in June 2007, using the Sun Java System Application Server (proprietary version of GlassFish) 9.0 Platform Edition, UltraSPARC T1-based Sun Fire server and PostgreSQL 8.2.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] This result of 778.14 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard compares favourably with the 874 JOPS@Standard with Oracle 10 on an Itanium-based HP-UX system.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In August 2007, Sun submitted an improved benchmark score of 813.73 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] With the system under test at a reduced price, the price/performance improved from $84.98/JOPS to $70.57/JOPS.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The default configuration of PostgreSQL uses only a small amount of dedicated memory for performance-critical purposes such as caching database blocks and sorting.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] This limitation is primarily because older operating systems required kernel changes to allow allocating large blocks of shared memory.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL.org provides advice on basic recommended performance practice in a wiki.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In April 2012, Robert Haas of EnterpriseDB demonstrated PostgreSQL 9.2's linear CPU scalability using a server with 64 cores.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Matloob Khushi performed benchmarking between PostgreSQL 9.0 and MySQL 5.6.15 for their ability to process genomic data.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In his performance analysis he found that PostgreSQL extracts overlapping genomic regions eight times faster than MySQL using two datasets of 80,000 each forming random human DNA regions.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Insertion and data uploads in PostgreSQL were also better, although general searching ability of both databases was almost equivalent.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] 64-bit Power ISA), SPARC (also 64-bit), MIPS and PA-RISC.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] It was also known to work on some other platforms (while not been tested on for years, i.e. for latest versions).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] , which can be used to enter SQL queries directly, or execute them from a file.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] In addition, psql provides a number of meta-commands and various shell-like features to facilitate writing scripts and automating a wide variety of tasks; for example tab completion of object names and SQL syntax.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] (GUI) administration tool for PostgreSQL, which is supported on many computer platforms.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The program is available in more than a dozen languages.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The second incarnation (named pgAdmin II) was a complete rewrite, first released on January 16, 2002.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] and then released under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] framework allowing it to run on most common operating systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The query tool includes a scripting language called pgScript for supporting admin and development tasks.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] announced that with the shift towards web-based models, work has begun on pgAdmin 4 with the aim to facilitate cloud deployments.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to perform essential PostgreSQL database development tasks from a web-based console.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to work with cloud databases without the need to open firewalls.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] AJAX/JavaScript-driven web interface for PostgreSQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Allows browsing, maintaining and creating data and database objects via a web browser.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] management for commonly used scripts, among other features.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Installers are available for Windows, Macintosh, and Linux, and a simple cross-platform archive that runs from a script.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Base can be used as a front-end for PostgreSQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] The pgBadger PostgreSQL log analyzer generates detailed reports from a PostgreSQL log file.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] pgDevOps is a suite of web tools to install & manage multiple PostgreSQL versions, extensions, and community components, develop SQL queries, monitor running databases and find performance problems.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] is a simple web-based administration tool for PostgreSQL and others, written in PHP.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] pgBackRest is a backup and restore tool for PostgreSQL that provides support for full, differential, and incremental backups.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] pgaudit is a PostgreSQL extension that provides detailed session and/or object audit logging via the standard logging facility provided by PostgreSQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Postgresus is an open source backup tool with GUI for scheduled backups with support of external sources (S3, NAS, FTP, Google Drive, Google Cloud, etc.) and notifications to external services (Slack, Discord, Telegram, SMTP, etc.).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] A number of companies offer proprietary tools for PostgreSQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] They often consist of a universal core that is adapted for various specific database products.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] These tools mostly share the administration features with the open source tools but offer improvements in data modeling, importing, exporting or reporting.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] Due to its permissive open-source license and extensible architecture, a broad ecosystem has developed around PostgreSQL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/postgresql] This includes numerous companies offering dedicated support and hosting, as well as several forks and derivative databases that adapt PostgreSQL for specific workloads.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/relational-database-management-system] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Replication in space or in time is often linked to scheduling algorithms.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Access to a replicated entity is typically uniform with access to a single non-replicated entity.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The replication itself should be transparent to an external user.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] In a failure scenario, a failover of replicas should be hidden as much as possible with respect to quality of service.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] When one leader replica is designated via leader election to process all the requests, the system is using a primary-backup or primary-replica scheme, which is predominant in high-availability clusters.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] In comparison, if any replica can process a request and distribute a new state, the system is using a multi-primary or multi-master scheme.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] In the latter case, some form of distributed concurrency control must be used, such as a distributed lock manager.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Load balancing differs from task replication, since it distributes a load of different computations across machines, and allows a single computation to be dropped in case of failure.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Load balancing, however, sometimes uses data replication (especially multi-master replication) internally, to distribute its data among machines.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Backup differs from replication in that the saved copy of data remains unchanged for a long period of time.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Replicas, on the other hand, undergo frequent updates and quickly lose any historical state.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Replication is one of the oldest and most important topics in the overall area of distributed systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Data replication and computation replication both require processes to handle incoming events.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Processes for data replication are passive and operate only to maintain the stored data, reply to read requests and apply updates.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Computation replication is usually performed to provide fault-tolerance, and take over an operation if one component fails.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] In both cases, the underlying needs are to ensure that the replicas see the same events in equivalent orders, so that they stay in consistent states and any replica can respond to queries.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Database replication involves maintaining copies of the same data on multiple machines, typically implemented through three main approaches: single-leader, multi-leader, and leaderless replication.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] In single-leader (also called primary/replica) replication, one database instance is designated as the leader (primary), which handles all write operations.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The leader logs these updates, which then propagate to replica nodes.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Each replica acknowledges receipt of updates, enabling subsequent write operations.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Replicas primarily serve read requests, though they may serve stale data due to replication lag – the delay in propagating changes from the leader.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] In multi-master replication (also called multi-leader), updates can be submitted to any database node, which then propagate to other servers.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] This approach is particularly beneficial in multi-data center deployments, where it enables local write processing while masking inter-data center network latency.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] However, it introduces substantially increased costs and complexity which may make it impractical in some situations.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The most common challenge that exists in multi-master replication is transactional conflict prevention or resolution when concurrent modifications occur on different leader nodes.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Most synchronous (or eager) replication solutions perform conflict prevention, while asynchronous (or lazy) solutions have to perform conflict resolution.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] For instance, if the same record is changed on two nodes simultaneously, an eager replication system would detect the conflict before confirming the commit and abort one of the transactions.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] A lazy replication system would allow both transactions to commit and run a conflict resolution during re-synchronization.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Conflict resolution methods can include techniques like last-write-wins, application-specific logic, or merging concurrent updates.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] However, replication transparency can not always be achieved.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] When data is replicated in a database, they will be constrained by CAP theorem or PACELC theorem.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] In the NoSQL movement, data consistency is usually sacrificed in exchange for other more desired properties, such as availability (A), partition tolerance (P), etc.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Various data consistency models have also been developed to serve as Service Level Agreement (SLA) between service providers and the users.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Active (real-time) storage replication is usually implemented by distributing updates of a block device to several physical hard disks.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] This way, any file system supported by the operating system can be replicated without modification, as the file system code works on a level above the block device driver layer.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] It is implemented either in hardware (in a disk array controller) or in software (in a device driver).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The most basic method is disk mirroring, which is typical for locally connected disks.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The storage industry narrows the definitions, so *mirroring* is a local (short-distance) operation.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] A replication is extendable across a computer network, so that the disks can be located in physically distant locations, and the primary/replica database replication model is usually applied.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The purpose of replication is to prevent damage from failures or disasters that may occur in one location – or in case such events do occur, to improve the ability to recover data.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] For replication, latency is the key factor because it determines either how far apart the sites can be or the type of replication that can be employed.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The main characteristic of such cross-site replication is how write operations are handled, through either asynchronous or synchronous replication; synchronous replication needs to wait for the destination server's response in any write operation whereas asynchronous replication does not.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Synchronous replication guarantees "zero data loss" by the means of atomic write operations, where the write operation is not considered complete until acknowledged by both the local and remote storage.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Most applications wait for a write transaction to complete before proceeding with further work, hence overall performance decreases considerably.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Inherently, performance drops proportionally to distance, as minimum latency is dictated by the speed of light.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] For 10 km distance, the fastest possible roundtrip takes 67 μs, whereas an entire local cached write completes in about 10–20 μs.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] In asynchronous replication, the write operation is considered complete as soon as local storage acknowledges it.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Remote storage is updated with a small lag.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Performance is greatly increased, but in case of a local storage failure, the remote storage is not guaranteed to have the current copy of data (the most recent data may be lost).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Semi-synchronous replication typically considers a write operation complete when acknowledged by local storage and received or logged by the remote server.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The actual remote write is performed asynchronously, resulting in better performance but remote storage will lag behind the local storage, so that there is no guarantee of durability (i.e., seamless transparency) in the case of local storage failure.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Point-in-time replication produces periodic snapshots which are replicated instead of primary storage.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] This is intended to replicate only the changed data instead of the entire volume.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] As less information is replicated using this method, replication can occur over less-expensive bandwidth links such as iSCSI or T1 instead of fiberoptic lines.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Many distributed filesystems use replication to ensure fault tolerance and avoid a single point of failure.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Many commercial synchronous replication systems do not freeze when the remote replica fails or loses connection – behaviour which guarantees zero data loss – but proceed to operate locally, losing the desired zero recovery point objective.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Techniques of wide-area network (WAN) optimization can be applied to address the limits imposed by latency.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] File-based replication conducts data replication at the logical level (i.e., individual data files) rather than at the storage block level.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] There are many different ways of performing this, which almost exclusively rely on software.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] A kernel driver (specifically a filter driver) can be used to intercept calls to the filesystem functions, capturing any activity as it occurs.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] This uses the same type of technology that real-time active virus checkers employ.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] At this level, logical file operations are captured like file open, write, delete, etc.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The kernel driver transmits these commands to another process, generally over a network to a different machine, which will mimic the operations of the source machine.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Like block-level storage replication, the file-level replication allows both synchronous and asynchronous modes.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] In synchronous mode, write operations on the source machine are held and not allowed to occur until the destination machine has acknowledged the successful replication.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Synchronous mode is less common with file replication products although a few solutions exist.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] File-level replication solutions allow for informed decisions about replication based on the location and type of the file.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] For example, temporary files or parts of a filesystem that hold no business value could be excluded.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The data transmitted can also be more granular; if an application writes 100 bytes, only the 100 bytes are transmitted instead of a complete disk block (generally 4,096 bytes).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] This substantially reduces the amount of data sent from the source machine and the storage burden on the destination machine.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Drawbacks of this software-only solution include the requirement for implementation and maintenance on the operating system level, and an increased burden on the machine's processing power.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Similarly to database transaction logs, many file systems have the ability to journal their activity.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The journal can be sent to another machine, either periodically or in real time by streaming.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] On the replica side, the journal can be used to play back file system modifications.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is Microsoft's System Center Data Protection Manager (DPM), released in 2005, which performs periodic updates but does not offer real-time replication.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] This is the process of comparing the source and destination file systems and ensuring that the destination matches the source.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The key benefit is that such solutions are generally free or inexpensive.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The downside is that the process of synchronizing them is quite system-intensive, and consequently this process generally runs infrequently.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is rsync.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] In a paging operating system, pages in a paging file are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] In IBM's VSAM, index data are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Another example of using replication appears in distributed shared memory systems, where many nodes of the system share the same page of memory.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] This usually means that each node has a separate copy (replica) of a specific page.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Many classical approaches to replication are based on a primary-backup model where one device or process has unilateral control over one or more other processes or devices.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] For example, the primary might perform some computation, streaming a log of updates to a backup (standby) process, which can then take over if the primary fails.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] This approach is common for replicating databases, despite the risk that if a portion of the log is lost during a failure, the backup might not be in a state identical to the primary, and transactions could then be lost.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] A weakness of primary-backup schemes is that only one is actually performing operations.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Fault-tolerance is gained, but the identical backup system doubles the costs.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] 1985, the distributed systems research community began to explore alternative methods of replicating data.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] An outgrowth of this work was the emergence of schemes in which a group of replicas could cooperate, with each process acting as a backup while also handling a share of the workload.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Computer scientist Jim Gray analyzed multi-primary replication schemes under the transactional model and published a widely cited paper skeptical of the approach "The Dangers of Replication and a Solution".
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] He argued that unless the data splits in some natural way so that the database can be treated as *n* disjoint sub-databases, concurrency control conflicts will result in seriously degraded performance and the group of replicas will probably slow as a function of *n*.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Gray suggested that the most common approaches are likely to result in degradation that scales as *O(n³)*.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] His solution, which is to partition the data, is only viable in situations where data actually has a natural partitioning key.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] In the 1985–1987, the virtual synchrony model was proposed and emerged as a widely adopted standard (it was used in the Isis Toolkit, Horus, Transis, Ensemble, Totem, Spread, C-Ensemble, Phoenix and Quicksilver systems, and is the basis for the CORBA fault-tolerant computing standard).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Virtual synchrony permits a multi-primary approach in which a group of processes cooperates to parallelize some aspects of request processing.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] The scheme can only be used for some forms of in-memory data, but can provide linear speedups in the size of the group.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] A number of modern products support similar schemes.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] For example, the Spread Toolkit supports this same virtual synchrony model and can be used to implement a multi-primary replication scheme; it would also be possible to use C-Ensemble or Quicksilver in this manner.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] WANdisco permits active replication where every node on a network is an exact copy or replica and hence every node on the network is active at one time; this scheme is optimized for use in a wide area network (WAN).
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Modern multi-primary replication protocols optimize for the common failure-free operation.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] Chain replication is a popular family of such protocols.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] State-of-the-art protocol variants of chain replication offer high throughput and strong consistency by arranging replicas in a chain for writes.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] This approach enables local reads on all replica nodes but has high latency for writes that must traverse multiple nodes sequentially.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] A more recent multi-primary protocol, Hermes, combines cache-coherent-inspired invalidations and logical timestamps to achieve strong consistency with local reads and high-performance writes from all replicas.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] During fault-free operation, its broadcast-based writes are non-conflicting and commit after just one multicast round-trip to replica nodes.
[src:gcp-cloud-sql/replication-computing] This design results in high throughput and low latency for both reads and writes.
